Title: Aivana Doc – Hospital Pricing Profitability Assessment
Date: March 2026
Prepared for: Aivana Health Intelligence Pvt. Ltd.

1. Objective

Goal: Evaluate whether the proposed per‑doctor hospital pricing model for Aivana Doc (AI‑powered OPD documentation) is financially viable and profitable, considering realistic infrastructure costs (Supabase, Vercel, Gemini API, etc.).

2. Pricing Model Summary

Plans (from current pricing sheet):

Clinic Plan
- ₹2,499/doctor/month
- Best for: 1–4 doctors

Hospital Plan (volume pricing)
- 5–10 doctors: ₹1,999/doctor/month
- 11–25 doctors: ₹1,799/doctor/month
- 26–50 doctors: ₹1,599/doctor/month
- 51–100 doctors: ₹1,399/doctor/month
- 100+ doctors: Custom (target ~50%+ discount vs clinic)

Annual payment discount (for hospitals)
- Monthly: no discount (e.g., ₹1,999)
- Quarterly: ~5% discount
- Annual: ~20% discount → effective ₹1,599–₹1,279/doctor/month at higher tiers

Example effective monthly pricing (annual contracts)
- 10 doctors: ₹1,599/doctor ⇒ ₹15,990/month
- 20 doctors: ₹1,439/doctor ⇒ ₹28,780/month
- 50 doctors: ₹1,279/doctor ⇒ ₹63,950/month

3. Infrastructure Stack and Assumptions

Planned stack:
- Backend and Auth: Supabase (managed Postgres, auth, storage)
- Frontend and App hosting: Vercel (Next.js or similar)
- LLM and AI engine: Google Gemini API (for example, Gemini 3 Flash or Flash‑Lite for production)

Key assumptions (conservative):
- Consult volume per doctor:
  - 30 consults per day
  - 22 working days per month
  - Approximately 660 consults per doctor per month

- Tokens per consult (voice to text to notes):
  - 3,000 input tokens + 1,000 output tokens = 4,000 tokens per consult
  - Approximately 2.64 million tokens per doctor per month

- Gemini 3 Flash pricing (2026, approximate per 1,000 tokens):
  - Input: $0.0005 per 1,000 tokens
  - Output: $0.003 per 1,000 tokens

This is intentionally a heavy-usage assumption. With prompt optimization, Flash‑Lite, and caching, actual tokens per consult are usually lower.

4. Estimated Monthly Infrastructure Cost per Doctor

LLM cost (per doctor per month, with the assumptions above):
- Input:
  - 2.64 million tokens × $0.0005 per 1,000 ≈ $1.32
- Output:
  - 2.64 million tokens × $0.003 per 1,000 ≈ $7.92
- Total LLM cost ≈ $9.24 per doctor per month

At ₹83 ≈ $1:
- Approximately ₹765 per doctor per month

With lighter prompts or Flash‑Lite, realistic cost often reduces to ₹200–500 per doctor per month.

Shared infrastructure (per project, per month):
- Supabase Pro: $25–75 (₹2,000–6,000)
- Vercel Pro: $20–40 (₹1,600–3,300)
- Other tools (monitoring, logging, emails, etc.): about ₹2,000–4,000

Total fixed infrastructure (example): approximately ₹8,000–12,000 per month, shared across all customers and all doctors.

If a single multi‑tenant stack serves 100 doctors, then:
- Fixed infrastructure allocation is about ₹80–120 per doctor per month.

5. Revenue versus Direct Infrastructure Cost

5.1 Single 20‑Doctor Hospital (Annual Best Rate)

Revenue:
- 20 doctors × ₹1,439 per doctor ≈ ₹28,780 per month

LLM cost (conservative):
- 20 × ₹500–765 ≈ ₹10,000–15,300 per month
- Use midpoint ≈ ₹12,500 per month

Fixed infrastructure allocation (assuming 100 doctors on the platform):
- Per doctor: about ₹100 per month
- 20 doctors ⇒ about ₹2,000 per month

Total direct infrastructure cost:
- Approximately ₹14,500 per month

Gross margin on infrastructure:
- Revenue: ₹28,780
- Direct cost: ₹14,500
- Gross profit: about ₹14,280 per month
- Infrastructure gross margin: about 50 percent

With more realistic, optimized LLM usage (₹300 per doctor per month), the margin exceeds 65–70 percent.

5.2 50‑Doctor Hospital (Annual Best Rate)

Revenue:
- 50 × ₹1,279 ≈ ₹63,950 per month

LLM cost (assume ₹400–700 per doctor):
- Midpoint ₹550 × 50 ≈ ₹27,500 per month

Fixed infrastructure allocation (100–150 total doctors):
- Assume about ₹80 per doctor → 50 × 80 ≈ ₹4,000 per month

Total direct infrastructure cost:
- Approximately ₹31,500 per month

Gross profit (infrastructure):
- ₹63,950 – ₹31,500 ≈ ₹32,450 per month
- Infrastructure gross margin: approximately 50–60 percent

Again, with better optimization, Gemini cost can drop materially, lifting margins.

6. Profitability Conclusion

Based on the above:
- Per‑doctor revenue (₹1,279–2,499) is significantly higher than realistic per‑doctor infrastructure cost (typically ≤ ₹500–1,000, often lower with Flash‑Lite and caching).
- Even under aggressive usage assumptions and no heavy optimization, direct gross margins of 50 percent or more on infrastructure alone are achievable.
- As the total number of doctors on the platform grows, fixed costs (Supabase, Vercel, tooling) are amortized, improving margin further.
- Therefore, this pricing model is fundamentally profitable from a unit‑economics and infrastructure‑cost perspective, assuming:
  - Multi‑tenant architecture (not one full stack per hospital),
  - Sensible LLM choice (Gemini Flash or Flash‑Lite, not only Pro),
  - Basic token usage optimization.

7. Key Risks and Non‑Infrastructure Cost Drivers

While infrastructure costs are favorable, profitability can be eroded by:

1. Sales and Customer Acquisition Cost (CAC)
   - High‑touch enterprise sales for small deals (5–10 doctors) can make CAC payback longer.
   - Mitigation:
     - Standardized demos, partner channels, and a focused ideal customer profile (for example, 10–50‑doctor hospitals).

2. Support and Onboarding Load
   - On‑site training, EMR/HMS integrations, and 24/7 WhatsApp support consume time.
   - If you promise these for very small contracts, margin shrinks.
   - Mitigation:
     - Limit on‑site training in lower tiers or make it a paid add‑on.
     - Use remote onboarding and recorded training content.

3. Overuse of Expensive LLM Models
   - Using Gemini Pro for every request instead of Flash or Flash‑Lite can multiply token cost.
   - Mitigation:
     - Route most traffic to cheaper models.
     - Use Pro only for complex or rare operations.
     - Implement context caching and prompt compression.

4. Inefficient Architecture
   - Spinning up separate Supabase and Vercel projects per hospital instead of a multi‑tenant system increases both complexity and cost.
   - Mitigation:
     - Design early for multi‑tenancy (for example, organization or hospital scoping).
     - Centralize logging and monitoring.

8. Recommendations

- Keep current per‑doctor pricing bands; they are comfortably profitable against infrastructure.
- Standardize on Gemini Flash or Flash‑Lite as the default engine; reserve Pro for special cases.
- Enforce multi‑tenant architecture to share Supabase, Vercel, and observability costs across all hospitals.
- Treat on‑site training, custom integrations, and dedicated support as add‑ons or bundle them only in larger contracts (for example, 20–30 doctors or more).
- Build a simple internal “unit economics” spreadsheet where you track:
  - Doctors per customer
  - Tokens per consult
  - Gemini cost per month
  - Infrastructure cost per month
  - Revenue and gross margin per customer

This will let you monitor in real time if any hospital or segment is drifting towards unprofitable usage, and adjust pricing or product limits accordingly.
